Oil and gas production is a global industry, with operations ranging from small private wells to large offshore developments [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]. The production process typically involves the following steps:
* Wellheads feeding into production and test manifolds [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]
* Gathering system, which collects the well-stream from multiple wells [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]
* Gas oil separation plant (GOSP), where the well-stream is separated into its various components [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]

The well-stream can consist of a range of hydrocarbons, including:
* Gas (methane, butane, propane, etc.) [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]
* Condensates (medium density hydrocarbons) [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]
* Crude oil [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]
* Unwanted components, such as water, carbon dioxide, salts, sulfur, and others [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 15]

In terms of global energy consumption, oil and gas play a significant role, with:
* 81.1% of the world's primary energy consumption coming from fossil fuels in 2012 [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135]
* 32.4% of the world's primary energy consumption coming from oil production in 2012 [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135]
* Total oil and gas production estimated at 6.4 billion tons of oil equivalent per year in 2012 [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135]
* Proven reserves of oil and gas estimated to last for about 56 years [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135]

The industry is also exploring unconventional sources of oil and gas, including:
* Tar sands in Venezuela and Canada [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 11]
* Shale oil and gas in the US and other countries [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 11]
* Coal bed methane and synthetic diesel from natural gas [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 11]
* Biodiesel and bioethanol from biological sources [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 11]
* Methane hydrates, which could potentially double available resources [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 11]

