It seems like you're inquiring about oil. Oil is a hydrocarbon that originates from ancient plants and animals, with its formation dating back to 250-290 or 290-350 million years ago [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 33]. The oil and gas are pressurized in the pores of the absorbent formation rock, and when a well is drilled into the reservoir structure, the hydrostatic formation pressure drives the hydrocarbons out of the rock and up into the well [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 33]. 

Some of the world's largest oil deposits are tar sands, where the volatile compounds have evaporated from shallow sandy formations, leaving huge volumes of bitumen-soaked sands [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 33]. These tar sands can be found in areas like Canada (Alberta) and Venezuela, with estimated reserves of 250 billion barrels, equivalent to the total reserves of Saudi Arabia [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 137]. 

Oil production accounts for 32.4% of the world's primary energy consumption, with total oil and gas production estimated at 6.4 billion tons of oil equivalent per year [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135]. Proven reserves of oil are estimated at 201 billion tons of oil equivalent, which is expected to last for about 56 years [ABB Oil & Gas Production Handbook, Page 135].

